<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-975-400  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 975 400.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Dec 18 1989 v6 n50 p109(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM staff cuts target 'dead wood'.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burke, Steven.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (costs).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Cost ReductionPersonnelBusiness Planning.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steven BurkeandM;Unlike IBM's previous efforts to cut its bloated work force, the lateststaff-reduction program is no golden handshake.andM;Rather, IBM is determined to get rid of dead wood, analysts said, and thecompany isn't paying a king's ransom to get targeted employees to leave.andM;&quot;This is about as close to a layoff as you can get without calling it that,&quot;said Richard Imershein, senior vice president of market researcher GartnerGroup Inc. in Stamford, Conn.andM;Some employees are going to be &quot;heavily encouraged&quot; to take advantage of theprogram, said Imershein.andP;  Those not accepting could be offered a position in&quot;Nome, Alaska,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;It is my understanding they [IBM upper management] are going to startgetting pretty hard-core,&quot; said an IBM sales representative who did not wantto be identified.andP;  &quot;They're putting a lot of pressure on people to perform.&quot;andM;IBM is under intense pressure from Wall Street.andP;  Two weeks ago, IBM announcedits plan to trim $1 billion from its U.S.andP;  operations in 1990 by cutting10,000 jobs.andP;  Because IBM has a no-layoff policy, it must use financialincentives to entice employees into early retirement.andP;  But Wall Street wasnot satisfied and is pressing for IBM to discard that policy and slash 40,000to 50,000 jobs to improve its earnings.andM;In 1988, in an effort to remove 6,500 employees from the payroll, IBM offeredsuch lucrative financial incentives that it lost many of its most experiencedand talented employees.andP;  This time, the new program is far less generous.andM;The 1988 program paid manufacturing employees double their annual salary plusa $25,000 bonus for leaving.andP;  Employees at corporate headquarters were paidfour weeks' salary for each year of service up to two years' salary.andM;The new program, in contrast, offers eligible employees one week of pay forevery six months of service up to one year's salary.andM;IBM officials contend it is unfair to compare the two programs.andP;  During the1988 cutback, IBM phased out manufacturing operations at five U.S.andO;locations.andM;Employee performance will not be used to determine who is eligible, said IBMspokeswoman Rita Black in White Plains, N.Y.andP;  The determination will be basedon the productivity and resources at each of IBM's 600 U.S.andP;  locations.andM;&quot;The corporation looks at specific skill groups,&quot; said Black.andP;  &quot;If too manypeople [in a specific skill group] have applied for the program, the decisionon who is allowed to leave the company will be based on seniority.&quot; IBMemployees who are eligible will have until Feb.andP;  9 to apply for the program.andO;</TEXT></DOC>